5. For the amniota data, calculate the number of NAs in the egg_mass_g column sorted by taxonomic class; i.e. how many NAs are present in the egg_mass_g column in birds, mammals, and reptiles? Does this results make sense biologically? How do these results affect your interpretation of NAs?

amniota %>%
  group_by(class) %>%
  select(class, egg_mass_g) %>% 
  naniar::miss_var_summary(order=T)
## Warning: `cols` is now required.
## Please use `cols = c(data)`
## # A tibble: 3 x 4
## # Groups:   class [3]
##   class    variable   n_miss pct_miss
##   <chr>    <chr>       <int>    <dbl>
## 1 Aves     egg_mass_g   4914     50.1
## 2 Mammalia egg_mass_g   4953    100  
## 3 Reptilia egg_mass_g   6040     92.0

+As should probably be expected, mammals have entirely NA data in their egg_mass_g column, and reptiles have close to 90%. This makes sense–in all mammals (excluding platypi) and many reptiles, infants are born live; no eggs are laid. Thus, no mass is inputted. +Some NAs are then the result of missing data; others are a result of data that cannot possibly exist. These two possibilities are distinct.

amphibio2 <- amphibio %>%
